Microlensing program

This is a program written by Britta Hansen (now Newby) while working at the Canadian Institute for Theoretical Astrophysics in Toronto, under the
supervision of Dr. Kelsey Hoffman. 

This program has various C function which take input parameters about a transiting stellar system. The parameters can include
i = inclination
a = semi-major axis
e = ellipticity
m = microlensing presence
l = limb darkening presence

Once the parameters are given, the program will compute the hypothetical light curve of the transit from our viewing angle. The result is printed to 
a data file ending in .dat. 
le 

The file structure is as folllows:
transit.c is the base program without limb darkening

To compile use gcc -lm -o transit transit.c

To run the program try
./transit -h	//lists help functions
./transit -r 0.1 -t 13500 -c 1 -d 1 -l 1 -m 1 -v 10000 -a 1 -b 0.5	// good starting functions

The results are output in transit.dat
To view the results in gnuplot, set xrange, set yrange, then run
plot "transit.dat" using 1:2 with linespoints

To analyze the result and compare to Kepler data, use Chi-squared functions. 
